## The Drop Direction Rule

This is the single most important visual rule in pear drop earrings, and it is violated in lower-quality listings and knockoff designs more often than buyers realize.

In pear stud earrings, the point faces upward — toward the crown of the head. The rounded belly sits near the earlobe and the tip reaches skyward. That orientation creates the classic teardrop shape because the stone is resting against the lobe and the visual weight is at the top.

In pear drop earrings, the geometry must invert. When the stone hangs below the earlobe, the point should face downward — toward the chin. The belly is at the top (closest to the ear), and the tip extends downward as the earring swings. This is the correct orientation for a pear drop, and it creates the true teardrop in motion: wide at the lobe, narrowing to a point below.

An earring that hangs with the point upward in a drop setting looks wrong. The narrowest part of the stone is closest to the ear, the design reads as inverted, and the visual balance is destroyed. Every well-made pear drop at Blue Nile follows the point-down convention. When comparing across brands or buying second-hand, verify the orientation in the product photography before purchasing — it is not always obvious in small thumbnail images.

The practical implication: when wearing a pear drop, the face-up view of the stone is not the primary display surface. You are displaying the silhouette and the motion. This is why drop earrings with clean outlines and strong profiles outperform cluster designs with heavy melee coverage — the movement is the feature, and busy designs obscure it.

